blocks.name: jm2.27
blocks.content: Lemma 2.27 of [JonesMatijasevic] p. 697; rmY is a diophantine relation. 0 was excluded from the range of B and the lower limit of G was imposed because the source proof does not seem to work otherwise; quite possible I'm just missing something. The source proof uses both i and I; i has been changed to j to avoid collision. This theorem is basically nothing but substitution instances, all the work is done in ~ jm2.27a and ~ jm2.27c . Once Diophantine relations have been defined, the content of the theorem is "rmY is Diophantine" (Contributed by Stefan O'Rear, 4-Oct-2014.)

thm jm2.27dlem1(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1) {

} = {
  a1ii(wi(wceq(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), c1), cfv(cv(s1), c1))), diffss(s0, s1))
  a1ii(wi(wceq(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), c1), cfv(cv(s1), c1))), diffsc(s0, c0))
  a1ii(wi(wceq(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), c1), cfv(cv(s1), c1))), diffsc(s0, c1))
  a1ii(wi(wceq(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), c1), cfv(cv(s1), c1))), diffsc(s1, c0))

  syl6eq(cfv(cv(s0), c1), cfv(cv(s1), c1), cfv(cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0)), c1), wceq(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0))))
  fveq1(cv(s0), cres(cv(s1), co(nat1, cfz, c0)), c1)

thm jm2.27dlem2(class c0, class c1, class c2) {

  elfzle2(c0, nat1, c2)

}
